p_conc phosphorus concentration (mg/g) Note: to determine percent nutrient remaining e.g. percent nitrogen remaining = ((final_odw*n_conc)/(orig_odw*'control nitrogen concentration'))*100, where orig_odw is the corrected fresh weight to estimate initial oven dry weight, and 'control nitrogen concentration' is the average of the three nitrogen concentrations recorded from the control litter bags, for a particular species (i.e. for Scholochloa (020201), control nitrogen concentration = 1.01 (average of 0.72,1.26,1.06)) MilligramsPerGram

c_conc carbon concentration (mg/g) Note: to determine percent nutrient remaining e.g. percent nitrogen remaining = ((final_odw*n_conc)/(orig_odw*'control nitrogen concentration'))*100, where orig_odw is the corrected fresh weight to estimate initial oven dry weight, and 'control nitrogen concentration' is the average of the three nitrogen concentrations recorded from the control litter bags, for a particular species (i.e. for Scholochloa (020201), control nitrogen concentration = 1.01 (average of 0.72,1.26,1.06)) MilligramsPerGram

n_conc nitrogen concentration (mg/g) Note: to determine percent nutrient remaining e.g. percent nitrogen remaining = ((final_odw*n_conc)/(orig_odw*'control nitrogen concentration'))*100, where orig_odw is the corrected fresh weight to estimate initial oven dry weight, and 'control nitrogen concentration' is the average of the three nitrogen concentrations recorded from the control litter bags, for a particular species (i.e. for Scholochloa (020201), control nitrogen concentration = 1.01 (average of 0.72,1.26,1.06)) MilligramsPerGram

species species species of litter contained in litter bag
h2o_depth water depth (cm) water depth recorded at the litter bag site at retrieval
cell_num cell number cells were numbered 1 to 10 from west to east in the diked study area.

lb_site litter bag site litter bag sites represented the natural depth range for each species as observed during the 1987 growing season. Sites established in 1985 were used if they met this criteria; otherwise, new sites were established where previous sites had sparse or absent vegetation.
lb_num litter bag number number assigned to litter bag, in order to keep track of sample
day_in day litter bag deployed litter bags were deployed on one of three dates: 30-May-1988, 31-May-1988 and 1-June-1988;
month_in month litter bag deployed litter bags were deployed on one of three dates: 30-May-1988, 31-May-1988 and 1-June-1988;
year_in year litter bag deployed litter bags were deployed on one of three dates: 30-May-1988, 31-May-1988 and 1-June-1988;
fresh_wt fresh litter bag weight (g) Samples were dried to a constant weight (approx. 48 hours) at room temperature (20 degrees C), and approximately 10g was placed in a litter bag.
final_odw litter dry weight at collection (oven dry weight; g) samples were dried to a constant weight at 80 degrees C.
day_out day litter bag retrieved five collection dates: 1-June-1988 to 3-June-1988, 25-July-1988, 22-September-1988, 6-June-1989 to 7-June-1989, and 9-Aug-1989 to 11-Aug-1989
month_out month litter bag retrieved five collection dates: 1-June-1988 to 3-June-1988, 25-July-1988, 22-September-1988, 6-June-1989 to 7-June-1989, and 9-Aug-1989 to 11-Aug-1989
year_out year litter bag retrieved five collection dates: 1-June-1988 to 3-June-1988, 25-July-1988, 22-September-1988, 6-June-1989 to 7-June-1989, and 9-Aug-1989 to 11-Aug-1989
grnd_num ground number corresponds to subsample number ground for nutrient analysis

p_conc phosphorus concentration (mg/g) litter nutrient concentration; To reduce the number of samples analyzed for total carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus, ground samples were pooled by species, water depth and collection date prior to chemical analysis. When possible, five litter bag samples were combined to make 1 sample for nutrient analysis. Water depths were stratified into 30-cm intervals: i.e. 0 cm = unflooded, 1- 30 cm = shallow, 31-60 cm = medium,  60-90 cm = deep sites, and >90cm.

c_conc carbon concentration (mg/g) litter nutrient concentration; To reduce the number of samples analyzed for total carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus, ground samples were pooled by species, water depth and collection date prior to chemical analysis. When possible, five litter bag samples were combined to make 1 sample for nutrient analysis. Water depths were stratified into 30-cm intervals: i.e. 0 cm = unflooded, 1- 30 cm = shallow, 31-60 cm = medium,  60-90 cm = deep sites, and >90cm.

n_conc nitrogen concentration (mg/g) litter nutrient concentration; To reduce the number of samples analyzed for total carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus, ground samples were pooled by species, water depth and collection date prior to chemical analysis. When possible, five litter bag samples were combined to make 1 sample for nutrient analysis. Water depths were stratified into 30-cm intervals: i.e. 0 cm = unflooded, 1- 30 cm = shallow, 31-60 cm = medium,  60-90 cm = deep sites, and >90cm.

spec_code species code All macroinvertebrates were sorted to the appropriate taxonomic level required to determine trophic level, and the total number of each taxon was recorded. Identification to family was adequate, however Chironomidae were further classified to the Tanypodinae subfamily (predator) and all other subfamilies as Non-Tanypodinae (herbivore).
dev_stage developmental stage 0

trop_level trophic level Due to taxonomic problems with the invertebrates of wetlands and the overlap of the trophic categories suggested by Cummins (1973), 2 broad trophic levels were distinguished as herbivore-detrivore and predator-parasite.
indv_samp total individuals in sample To sort the individuals found in the activity traps, the rinsed samples were placed into a sorting tray and covered with a sugar solution. dimensionless

total_biomass_mg total biomass of sample (mg) A representative sample of all invertebrate taxa and size classes from all sorted samples (with the exception of emergence trap samples) were kept to determine biomass. The representative individuals were from each taxa and sample type were rinsed with distilled water and then placed in weighed and dried (105ºC for 24 hrs.) aluminum pans. The invertebrates were then dried at 105 ºC overnight and the pans were weighed again the following day. When 500 individuals of the same taxon or size class had been collected and weighed, where the mean weight was < 1.0mg, and 200 individuals from any taxa had a mean weight > 1.0 mg, these groups no longer had to be dried for their dry-weight determination (Ross and Murkin, 1989).

Species name Macrophyte species name At the beginning of the belowground macrophyte production study (1980-1982), roots and rhizomes were categorized into species.

day sampling day In order to estimate net annual belowground macrophyte production, core samples of the belowground biomass were harvested in the late spring and in the fall. Shoot initiation early in the growing season depletes most of the belowground standing crop, and therefore spring sampling was done quickly (within 2 weeks) to capture this state. Underground biomass then reaches its seasonal maxima in the fall and was captured with the fall sampling.

samp_per sample period identifies whether sample period was spring (1) or fall (2). 1 = spring- the spring sampling period began when the cattails started to flower. 2 = fall- the fall sampling period began during the last 2 weeks of september (starting september 15) and the first week of october.

zone sampling zone each cell was divided into 10 equal zones.These zones were marked permanently with transects and used each year. transects at each cell were grouped into 5 pairs (1 and 2, 3 and 4, 5 and 6, 7 and 8, and 9 and 10) for a total of 60 transect groups. each transect group was assigned a random number between 1 and 60 and then sampled in the resulting order.
